PART V: THE MIDDEN (THE UNDERCITY DUNGEON)
Location: The Quarantine Zone beneath the College
Function: Alfonso's quest, full dungeon crawl, Dagon revelation
Estimated Time: 2-3 hours

Overview: The Five Sections
The Midden is a complete, standalone dungeon with five distinct sections:
The Descent (Entry/Introduction)
The Frozen Tunnels (Navigation/Combat)
The Atronach Forge (Boss Fight - Alfonso's Goal)
The Augur's Domain (Optional/Revelation)
The Root Chamber (Dagon Discovery - Saijah's Goal)
GM Note: The Midden is dangerous. The party should be at full resources before entering. Nora can guide them (granting Advantage on navigation) if recruited.

Section 1: The Descent
Entry Point: Heavy iron gates at the base of the Hall of the Elements.
Read Aloud:
"The gates leading to the Midden are massive, rusted iron reinforced with glowing warning runes. A sign reads: 'QUARANTINE ZONE - ENTRY FORBIDDEN BY ORDER OF ARCH-MAGE AREN.'
The rhythmic THUD from below is deafening here. The ground vibrates with each pulse.
If you're going in, you'll need to break the sealΓÇöor find another way."
Options:
Break the Seal: Requires combined Might check (Hard, -4) or Destruction magic (costs 6 FP, creates noise).
Lockpick the Side Door: Guile (Lockpicking, Hard -2). Quieter but slower.
Nora's Secret Path: If she's with them, she shows a maintenance shaft (automatic success, no noise).
Once Inside:
Read Aloud:
"The temperature drops twenty degrees the moment you cross the threshold. The atmospheric ward doesn't extend down here.
You're standing at the top of a spiraling stone staircase that descends into frozen darkness. Icicles hang from the ceiling like stalactites. Steam rises from vents in the floor, freezing instantly into jagged crystals.
The walls are carved from ancient bedrockΓÇöolder than the College itself. This isn't a basement; it's the foundation. The original ruins the College was built upon.
The THUD echoes up the stairs, shaking loose snow and ice.
Below, you hear the chittering of insects and the low, static hum of something electrical."
The Descent: The party descends 200 feet. No encounters, just atmosphere. Let the dread build.

Section 2: The Frozen Tunnels
Layout: A maze of ice-coated stone corridors. The walls are lined with failed experiments in glass cagesΓÇömost dead, some still twitching.
Hazards:
Slippery Ice: Floors are Difficult Terrain (requires Agility checks to move quickly).
Steam Vents: Random vents erupt. Agility Save or 2 Fire damage.
The Pulse: Every 5 minutes (real time), the THUD strikes. Everyone makes Might Save (Standard) or knocked Prone.
Encounters:
Encounter A: Corrupted Ice Wraiths
Setup: Three Ice Wraiths emerge from the walls. They glow with sickly red light (Dagon corruption).
Read Aloud:
"Three serpentine forms materialize from the ice itselfΓÇöIce Wraiths, but wrong. Their bodies pulse with red, cancerous light. They screechΓÇönot the natural sound of wind through ice, but a metallic, grinding shriek.
They see you. They attack."
Combat:
3x Corrupted Ice Wraiths (TL 1 Skirmishers)
HP: 20 each
DR: 2 (immune to Cold)
Attacks: Frost Shard (4 Cold damage)
Special: Shove Attack - On hit, target makes Might Save or slides 10 feet (toward hazards or off ledges)
Tactics: They try to push characters into steam vents or off platforms.
Loot: Each wraith drops 1x Frost Salts (worth 50g, useful for alchemy).

Encounter B: The Chaurus Ambush
Setup: The tunnels narrow. The party must crawl through a tight passage.
Read Aloud:
"The tunnel ahead narrows to a crawlspace barely three feet high. The walls are slick with moisture and something... organic. It smells like rot and sulfur.
As you crawl through, you hear a wet, chittering sound behind you."
Combat:
A Chaurus Hunter bursts through the tunnel behind them, spitting acid.
1x Chaurus Hunter (TL 2 Elite)
HP: 60
DR: 4 (chitin armor)
Attacks:
Mandible Bite: 6 damage
Acid Spit: Cone attack (15 feet), 4 Acid damage + permanent -1 DR to metal armor until repaired
Weakness: Fire damage ignores DR
Tactics: It blocks retreat, forcing the party to fight in cramped quarters.
Loot:
2x Chaurus Eggs (worth 30g each, alchemy ingredient)
Damaged Iron Helmet (can be salvaged for parts)

Encounter C: The Rogue Experiment
Setup: The party finds a sealed laboratory door. Inside, something is screaming.
Read Aloud:
"A heavy iron door is sealed with frost. Through a narrow window, you see a laboratory in chaosΓÇöshattered alembics, overturned tables, scorch marks on the walls.
A humanoid figure staggers toward the window. It's a studentΓÇöor was. Their skin is grey, cracked like ceramic. Their eyes glow with unnatural blue light. They're trapped in a half-transformation, neither living nor construct.
They slam against the glass, screaming: 'Let me out! I'm still in here! Please!'"
The Choice:
Open the Door: The Experimental Failure attacks immediately (hostile, not in control).
Mercy Kill: Cast Destruction magic through the window to end its suffering.
Leave It: Walk away. The screaming follows them.
If They Fight:
1x Experimental Failure (TL 1 Minion)
HP: 25
DR: 3 (fused metal plates)
Attacks: Frost Touch (5 Cold damage, drains 2 FP on hit)
Special: When killed, releases psychic scream (all within 10 feet make Guile Save or Frightened for 2 rounds)
GM Note: This encounter is about moral weight. There's no "good" solution. Let the party feel the cost.

Section 3: The Atronach Forge (Boss Fight)
Location: A massive central chamber carved from bedrock.
Read Aloud:
"The tunnels open into a vast, circular chamber. At its center stands the Atronach ForgeΓÇöa massive brass-and-stone altar etched with Daedric runes that glow with pulsing purple light.
The forge is active. Arcs of purple lightning dance between the pillars. The air smells of sulfur and ozone.
And fused to the forge itself is a massive Storm AtronachΓÇöa hulking elemental of living lightning encased in jagged metal plating. Its body crackles and sparks. When it sees you, it roars, and the sound is thunder.
Behind it, the wall is covered in massive, black rootsΓÇöEldergleam rootsΓÇöbreaking through the stone. They're weeping black oil."
The Boss: Rogue Storm Atronach
TL 3 Boss (Elite-tier fight)
HP: 120
DR: 6 (reinforced with forge metal)
Attacks:
Chain Lightning: Ranged (30 feet), 8 Shock damage to primary target + arcs to 2 nearby targets for 4 damage each
Thunder Slam: Melee, 10 damage + knocks Prone in 10-foot radius
Static Field: Aura (15-foot radius). Anyone wearing metal armor takes 2 Shock damage per round while inside.
Weakness: Water-based magic doubles damage. Fire does nothing (it's made of lightning).
Behavior: Stays near forge. Uses terrain (steam vents, ice patches) to control battlefield.
Environmental Hazards:
The Forge Itself: Anyone within 5 feet of the forge takes 3 Fire damage per round from radiant heat.
Leyline Conduits: Four brass pillars around the room. If destroyed (HP 20 each, DR 0), the Atronach loses 20 HP (feedback damage).
Tactics:
Smart players will:
Destroy leyline pillars to weaken it
Lure it away from the forge (removes Static Field advantage)
Use water spells or splash it with water from broken pipes
Defeat:
When reduced to 0 HP:
Read Aloud:
"The Storm Atronach's form destabilizes. Lightning arcs wildly, striking the walls, the ceiling, the forge itself.
It collapses inward with a sound like a thunderclap, imploding into a pile of smoking metal and crystallized Void Salts.
The forge goes dark. The THUD from deeper below continues, but the static hum is gone."
Loot:
Void Salt Cluster (Alfonso's quest objective - glowing purple crystals, fist-sized)
2x Grand Soul Gems (empty)
Storm Atronach Core (enchanting component, worth 500g)
Daedric War Axe (leaning against the forge, +2 weapon)
GM Note: Alfonso now has what he needs to complete Sergius's quest. But the Midden has more secrets...

Section 4: The Augur's Domain (Optional)
Location: Behind a sealed door near the forge.
Read Aloud:
"Beyond the forge chamber, you find a sealed door glowing with wards. A voice echoes from withinΓÇönot a voice you hear, but one you feel inside your skull.
'Turn back. The light burns. But if you must see... ask your question, and I will answer.'"
The Augur of Dunlain:
A former student who attempted to transcend mortality. He succeededΓÇösort of. He is now a being of pure magical energy, a floating sphere of light fused to the College's leylines.
Interaction:
The party can ask one question each. The Augur answers truthfully but cryptically.
Example Questions/Answers:
"What is the Eye of Magnus?" - "A seed. A door. A lie wrapped in truth. It is not an artifact. It is an embryo."
"How do I break the Ring?" (Orion) - "The chain cannot be broken while the smith still breathes. But if the smith is killed, the chain will drag you into the dark with him."
"What is Hjolmar?" (Kyboh) - "A man who chose the hammer over mortality. He is half-smith, half-echo. The forge owns him as much as he owns it."
GM Note: The Augur provides foreshadowing and existential dread, but no concrete solutions.

Section 5: The Root Chamber (Dagon Revelation)
Location: The deepest point of the Midden, directly beneath the Hall of the Elements.
Setup: Following the black roots leads the party here.
Read Aloud:
"You follow the roots deeper. The tunnels give way to a natural cavernΓÇöfreezing, dark, and filled with the sound of dripping water.
The roots are everywhere here. Massive, black Eldergleam roots as thick as tree trunks, breaking through solid stone. They weep black oil that pools on the floor, hissing and smoking.
At the center of the cavern is a blast doorΓÇöreinforced steel, glowing with wards, sealed tight. The THUD is coming from behind it. You can feel it in your chest, in your teeth, in your soul.
THUD... THUD... THUD...
And tangled in the roots, impaled on a spike of black wood, is a corpse.
It's wearing robes marked with the symbol of Mehrunes DagonΓÇöa razor-edged star. In its skeletal hand is a half-burned map."
The Discovery:
The Corpse: A Dagon cultist, dead for weeks. Killed by the roots (they impaled him).
The Map: Shows a ritual site northeast of the College. Marked: "GATEWAY CONVERGENCE - WINTER SOLSTICE."
The Implication: The Dagon cult is trying to open a gate. They're using the Eye of Magnus and the corrupted Eldergleam roots as anchors.
Saijah's Reaction:
If Saijah is present:
Read Aloud (Saijah Only):
"The roots pulse when you approach. Not with lifeΓÇöwith hunger.
You feel the Eldergleam's scream echoing through them. The tree isn't just dying. It's being hollowed out. The roots are channels now, conduits for something else.
You realize: the corruption didn't just spread through Eastmarch. It traveled underground, through the roots, all the way here. The Dagon cult is using the tree's death to fuel the Eye.
They're not trying to destroy the world.
They're trying to unmake it."
GM Note: This is the major plot revelation for Arc 2. The Dagon cult's plan is now clear: use the dying Eldergleam as a leyline to power the Eye of Magnus, creating a gateway for Mehrunes Dagon himself.

Exit: Blowing the Grate
Setup: The party has what they need (Void Salts, intel). Time to leave.
Read Aloud:
"You return to the main Midden chamber. At the far end, you see a heavy iron grate covering a shaft leading downΓÇönot up.
Nora (if present) points: 'That goes to the ice shelf below the College. It's how students used to sneak out before the quarantine. If we blow the grate, we can drop straight to the frozen sea. Bypass the bridge entirely.'
Through the grate, you see open air and crashing waves hundreds of feet below."
The Choice:
Go Back Up: Return through the College, deliver Void Salts to Sergius, resupply, then leave via the bridge.
Blow the Grate: Use explosives or Destruction magic to blast it open. Drop to the ice shelf. Begin the journey north immediately.
If They Blow It:
Read Aloud:
"The grate explodes outward with a deafening roar. Shrapnel and ice shards rain down into the void.
You stand at the edge, looking down. It's a hundred-foot drop to a frozen shelf of ice jutting from the base of the College pillar.
One by one, you jump."
Descent Mechanic: Agility Save (Standard). Success = land safely. Failure = land hard (4 damage).
Arrival:
Read Aloud:
"You land on the ice shelf with a jarring impact. The wind screams around you. The Sea of Ghosts crashes against the rocks below, sending up plumes of freezing spray.
Looking up, the College looms above you like a frozen giant.
Looking north, you see nothing but endless whiteΓÇöthe frozen sea stretching to the horizon.
And in the distance, barely visible through the blizzard, you see it:
A spire of ice that catches the light wrong. It doesn't shine. It sings.
The Glacier that Sings. Hjolmar's forge.
You have a choice to make."
GM Note: If they blew the grate, they cannot easily return to the College. They're committed to the Hjolmar route. If they went back up, they can resupply and decide.

PART VI: THE JOURNEY NORTH (THE SINGING SEA)
Location: The Sea of Ghosts
Context: The party is traveling north to Hjolmar's forge. They must cross the Singing SeaΓÇöa field of frictionless ice.

1. The Approach
Read Aloud:
"You trek north for hours. The blizzard never stops. Visibility is measured in feet, not miles.
Eventually, the ground beneath you changes. The packed snow gives way to dark, glassy iceΓÇösmooth as a mirror, black as obsidian.
Kyboh's gloves begin to vibrate. Not with painΓÇöwith resonance. They're pulling north like a compass seeking iron.
You've reached the Singing Sea."
GM Note: Kyboh's gloves are reacting to Hjolmar's forge. They want to go home.

2. The Resonance Field (Physics Puzzle)
Concept: The ice here is frictionless. It's vibrating at a tonal frequency that eliminates all surface friction. Objects in motion stay in motion (Newton's First Law). Jumping off an object pushes it in the opposite direction (Newton's Third Law).
The Rules:
Jumping On: When a character jumps onto an Ice Floe from a static point, the Floe moves in the direction of the jump until it hits an obstacle.


Jumping Off: When a character jumps off a Floe, the character lands in the target square and the Floe is pushed in the opposite direction until it hits something.


Mass Matters:


Small Floes (1x1): Carry 1 person. Move fast.
Large Floes (2x2): Carry whole party. Require combined Might Check (or Kyboh alone) to start moving from standstill, but smash through small obstacles once moving.
The Water: If a Floe slides off the map or a player misses a jump, they fall into the Sea of Ghosts. 4 Cold damage immediately. Might Check to climb back onto nearest solid object. Failure = begin drowning.



3. The Three Stages
Stage 1: The Tutorial (The Straight Shot)
Setup: One Small Floe. Straight water. Rock wall at end.
Read Aloud:
"Before you is a simple test: a single ice floe floating in dark water. Beyond it, a rock wall. Between you and safety is twenty feet of frictionless ice."
Solution: Jump onto Floe (slides north). Hits wall. Jump off.
Lesson Learned: "It doesn't stop until it hits something."

Stage 2: The Ricochet (The Angle)
Setup: Large Floe. Jagged iceberg blocking direct path. Rocks staggered to east/west.
Read Aloud:
"The path ahead is blocked by a massive iceberg. You can't go straight. The floe will need to 'bounce' around it."
The Puzzle:
Jump East onto Floe ΓåÆ hits East Rock. Jump North off Floe? NoΓÇöthat pushes Floe South (wrong direction).
Solution:
The party must bank the floe like a billiards shot:
Jump onto Floe from South
Floe slides North, hits iceberg, stops
One person jumps West off the Floe
Floe slides East around the iceberg
Party jumps back on, rides it to destination
Alternative (Kyboh): He can "punch" the air (Kinetic Pulse from gloves) to propel the Floe without jumping off.

Stage 3: The Ferryman (The Sacrifice)
Setup: Massive open water. Only one Large Floe (The Ferry).
Read Aloud:
"The final stretch is a hundred feet of open water. There's only one floe large enough to carry all of you.
But to move it forward, someone has to jump backward off it."
The Problem: To propel the Ferry north, someone must jump southΓÇöleaving them behind.
Solutions:
The Sacrifice: One member stays behind. Ferry shoots north with rest of party. That person must then use Small Floes around the perimeter to build a path/retrieve vehicle.


Alfonso's Ghoul: If present, Alfonso orders Ghoul to jump off (propels Ferry forward). Ghoul left behind to drown/freeze. Ruthlessly efficient. Ylva loves it.


Kyboh's Engine: Kyboh stands on Ferry, punches south repeatedly (Kinetic Pulses). Acts as outboard motor. Risk: Each pulse requires d20 roll. On 1, gloves overload and crack the ice (Large Floe becomes Small, or Small sinks).



4. The Threat: Children of the Cold
Setup: While solving the puzzle, the party is attacked.
Read Aloud:
"As you navigate the ice, shapes materialize from the blizzardΓÇöthree serpentine forms made of frozen wind.
Ice Wraiths. But not attacking to kill.
Attacking to push."
Combat:
3x Ice Wraiths (TL 1 Skirmishers)
HP: 20 each
DR: 2 (immune to Cold)
Attacks:
Frost Shard: 4 Cold damage
Shove: On hit, Might Save or pushed 10 feet (toward water)
Special: They hover (ignore ice physics)
Tactics: They don't try to kill. They try to knock players off floes into the water.
Loot: 3x Frost Salts (worth 50g each).

5. The Destination
Read Aloud:
"The final floe slams into solid ground with a bone-jarring impact.
You've reached the base of the Singing Glacier.
It towers above youΓÇöa spire of translucent blue ice impossibly tall. And it's vibrating. Not subtly. The entire structure hums with a low, resonant frequency that makes your teeth ache and your bones itch.
The sound is like a choir of glass bellsΓÇöbeautiful and terrifying.
At the base, set into the ice, is a smooth surface with a Snowflake Sigil carved into it. There's no handle. No keyhole. Just the sigil."
The Key:
Kyboh must place his fused hands against the sigil.
Read Aloud:
"As you press your hands to the ice, the vibrations from the glacier sync with the broken resonance of your gloves.
For the first time since the overload, they don't hurt. They sing.
The snowflake sigil glows. The ice doesn't meltΓÇöit sublimates, turning to mist and revealing a passage into the heart of the glacier.
The way is open."

PART VII: THE MAKER'S FORGE (HJOLMAR)
Location: Interior of the Singing Glacier
Context: The party has arrived. This is the climax of Arc 2.

1. The Workshop
Read Aloud:
"You step through the mist and the howling wind stops instantly.
The interior of the glacier is a cathedral-like workshop carved from translucent blue ice. In the center is a Forge that burns with cold blue fireΓÇönot heat, but raw Magicka made visible.
Everything is oversized. The anvil is the size of a carriage. The hammers hanging on the wall are too heavy for a mortal to lift. Half-finished projects litter the tables: Stalhrim armor that hums with power, glass spheres containing captured storms, delicate clockwork mechanisms frozen in blocks of ice.
And at the anvil, working a piece of glowing metal with a hammer that rings like a bell, is the Maker.
He's massiveΓÇötwelve feet tall, built like a mountain. His skin is the color of weathered stone, his beard white as a blizzard. He wears an apron made of mammoth hide over intricate, ancient armor.
He doesn't stop working when you enter. The hammer falls. The anvil rings. The metal sings.
After a long moment, he speaks without turning.
'You are loud. Your heartbeats disrupt the resonance.'"
GM Note: Let this moment breathe. Hjolmar is ancient. He's not hostile, but he's not impressed.

2. The Recognition
Read Aloud:
"Slowly, the giant turns. His eyes are solid blue iceΓÇöno pupils, no whites, just frozen light.
He looks at the party, his expression unreadable.
Then his gaze lands on Kyboh. On the fused, smoking gloves.
The workshop goes silent.
'You.'
He crosses the room in two massive strides. The ground shakes. He grabs Kyboh's arm, lifting him off the ground effortlessly, bringing the gloves to eye level.
'I forged those to catch thunder. You used them to punch a wall.'
His grip is iron.
'You overloaded the Kinetic Matrix. You broke the loop. You are not a warrior. You are a child playing with a star.'
He's about to throw KybohΓÇöor crush himΓÇöwhen he stops.
He sniffs the air. He looks at Kyboh's chest, at his legs.
'Wait. You are wearing the Boots. And the Gloves. Together. And you are... standing.'
He drops Kyboh.
'Most mortals would be jelly. The resonance between those two artifacts creates a shearing force that tears bone apart. But you... your bones are vibrating in time with it. You are adapting.'
He smiles. It's terrifying.
'Fascinating. You are not a fool. You are a Crucible.'"

3. The Surgery (Removing the Curse)
Hjolmar's Dialogue:
"Sit. If I do not remove them now, they will eat your hands."
The Procedure:
Hjolmar gestures to a stone slab. Kyboh lies down.
Read Aloud:
"Hjolmar takes a Tonal Tuning Fork from his workbenchΓÇöa massive, U-shaped piece of metal inscribed with runes. He strikes it against the anvil.
The sound is a pure, piercing note that hurts your teeth and makes your vision blur.
He touches the vibrating fork to the fused gloves.
The grey ceramic shatters. Not breaksΓÇöshatters, like glass struck by a hammer. The fused skin releases. The gloves fall off, smoking and dead.
Kyboh's hands are raw, red, shakingΓÇöbut they are his again.
The calcification on his forearms and knees turns to dust and flakes away.
The Psychic Static in his skull stops.
The silence is blissful."
Mechanical Effect:
Arcane Burnout removed (no more -2 Guile penalty)
Hands are free (can wear other gloves)
Calcification gone (no more spreading corruption)
But:
Read Aloud:
"Hjolmar picks up the dead gloves, examining them.
'The shell is intact. But the heart is burnt out. I cannot fix this with steel.'
He turns to the party.
'I need a new core. Something that can handle the resonance you are generating. The Dwemer built such a thing: a Cognitive Soul Gem. They called it the Aetherial Matrix.'"

4. The Quest Hook (Mzinchaleft)
Hjolmar's Dialogue:
"The Dwemer tried to map a soul onto a crystal lattice to achieve immortality. They failed. But the latticeΓÇöthe Aetherial MatrixΓÇöit is perfect. It can hold an infinite charge without breaking.
Go to Mzinchaleft. Deep in the ice. There is a sealed archive thereΓÇöthe Cognitorium. Find the Matrix. Bring it to me.
And I will forge you a weapon that will not break, no matter how hard you hit the world."
The Warning:
"The Cognitorium is not empty. The Dwemer left their toys behind. Spiders. Spheres. Centurions. They are running on standby power, glitching, dangerous.
Do not break the Matrix when you retrieve it. I do not have a replacement."
The Ultimatum:
"Do not return without it."
GM Note: Hjolmar will not entertain arguments. He's given them the quest. They leave, complete it, or don't return. There's no time pressure from himΓÇöbut the Hemming Clock is still ticking.

5. The Choice (Arc 2 Ends Here)
Read Aloud:
"You step back out into the blizzard. The Singing Glacier hums behind you.
Ahead, the frozen sea stretches in all directions.
South: The College. Riften. Hemming Black-Briar dying of plague. Danica waitingΓÇöor not waitingΓÇödepending on how long you take.
West: Mzinchaleft. The Aetherial Matrix. Power. The completion of Kyboh's quest.
You have a choice to make.
What do you do?"
GM Note: Do NOT force the decision. Let the players debate. Let them feel the weight. This is the pivot point of the entire campaign.
Options:
Go to Mzinchaleft (Arc 3) - Pursue power. Risk arriving too late for Hemming.
Go to Riften (Future Arc) - Save Hemming. Kyboh's gloves stay broken.
Split the Party (Chaos option) - Some go to Mzinchaleft, some to Riften. GM must run parallel tracks.
End Arc 2.

